Introduction

This report provides an mini exploration of differences in juvenile snowshoe hare trap counts and weights from 1999-2012 in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest in Interior Alaska (Kielland et al.2017). This capture-recapture study explores the snowshoe hare, which is a keystone prey species in the northern boreal forests in 3 different sites (Black Spruce, Mature and Riparian) (Kielland et al.2017). This report first explores the juvenile snowshoe hare trap counts annually from 1998 to 2012. Then explores the juvenile snowshoe hare weights by sex and site. Followed by a more focused comparison of weights between male and female juvenile hares. Lastly, explores the relationship between juvenile weights and hind foot length.

Data and anyalses

The data on snowshoe hares was collected by capture-recapture by Dr.Knut Kielland and colleagues at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest in Fairbanks, Alaska (Kielland et al.2017). The data contain 3,197 observations of snowshoe hares, collected from 1999-2012 over three sites (Black Spruce, Mature and Riparian). Following exploratory visualization, juvenile weights (grams) and hind foot lengths (millimeters) are compared by two-sample t-test using a significance level (\(\alpha\)) of 0.05 and differences between groups are described by Cohens d effect size. The relationship between weight and hind foot length is explored by simple linear regression (All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.4.1717)

Juvenile hare initial investigation

Section 1: Annual juvenile hare trap counts

Figure 1 takeaways

There is a general trend of decreasing counts of juvenile hare trappings from 1999-2012, there is a large spread of annual juvenile hare trap counts, ranging from 2 to 126. The mean count of juvenile hares trapped annually is 31.5 and median is 18.5. The changes from year to year show no consistent trend, other than a large drop after the maximum count year in 1999, this could be due to the fact that these are absolute counts and are impacted by the effort of researchers. I would suggest standardizing the juvenile hare population by randomly selecting uniform sample sizes for each year.

Visualizations for juvenile hare weights takeaways

There is a visible difference in counts of juvenile hares that had weights recorded between sites. The Riparian site has the largest counts of weights for both male and female juvenile hares, and the Black Spruce site has the fewest counts of weights for males, females and unknown. The distribution of weights of juvenile hares between sites and sexes have no distinct trend, although the central tendency of female weights is below male weights at each site. The biggest take away is that the large differences in counts can impact the visible trends.

Table 3 takeaways

The difference in mean weight between male and female juvenile hares is 90.5 (g), and the results of the t-test have a p-value of 0.0070933 meaning that if these samples were drawn from populations with the same mean, the probability of taking two random samples with means at least as different as the sample means we found by random chance (taking into account Cohens d = 0.29 and n = 363) is a 0.7%. Therefore we can reject the null hypothesis that the samples were drawn from populations with the same mean.
